editorial:
**Trick — control print position relative to recursion call**:

For `1..n` in increasing order without a loop:
- Recurse first (`printForward(n-1)`), THEN push `n`. Stack unwinds in increasing order.

For `n..1` in decreasing order:
- Push `n` FIRST, then recurse (`printReverse(n-1)`). Top-of-stack action gives decreasing.

```javascript
function stationSkipPrint(n) {
  const forward = [];
  const reverse = [];
  function pf(k) {
    if (k < 1) return; // base
    pf(k - 1);
    forward.push(k);
  }
  function pr(k) {
    if (k < 1) return; // base
    reverse.push(k);
    pr(k - 1);
  }
  pf(n);
  pr(n);
  return { forward, reverse };
}
```

**Time**: O(n). **Space**: O(n) stack + O(n) output.

Key lesson: same recursion can produce *opposite* orders just by swapping work-before-call vs work-after-call.

