editorial:
**Insert-at-every-position approach (pure recursion, no swap-mutation)**:
- Base: `s.length <= 1 → [s]`.
- Recurrence: get permutations of `s.slice(1)`. For each smaller permutation `p`, insert `s[0]` at every position 0..p.length to build new permutations.

```javascript
function permuteString(s) {
  function perm(str) {
    if (str.length <= 1) return [str];
    const first = str[0];
    const rest = perm(str.slice(1));
    const result = [];
    for (const p of rest) {
      for (let i = 0; i <= p.length; i++) {
        result.push(p.slice(0, i) + first + p.slice(i));
      }
    }
    return result;
  }
  return perm(s).sort();
}
```

**Time**: O(n * n!). **Space**: O(n * n!).

**Note vs backtracking**: This is the *insertion* recursion form — distinct from backtracking (which mutates a current path with explicit undo). The recursive call returns *all* sub-permutations and we *build* on top — no enumeration tree with prune/restore.

