editorial:
**Two-helper recursion** — only the call stack is allowed as auxiliary memory.

**Helper 1 — `insertAtBottom(stack, x)`**: place `x` at the bottom of the stack.
- Base: stack empty → push `x`.
- Else: pop top into a local var, recurse to insert `x` at bottom of the smaller stack, then push the local var back. The local var lives on the call stack.

**Helper 2 — `reverse(stack)`**: reverse the entire stack.
- Base: stack empty → return.
- Else: pop top, recursively reverse rest, then `insertAtBottom(stack, top)`.

```javascript
function reverseStack(stack) {
  function insertAtBottom(s, x) {
    if (s.length === 0) {
      s.push(x);
      return;
    }
    const top = s.pop();
    insertAtBottom(s, x);
    s.push(top);
  }
  function reverse(s) {
    if (s.length === 0) return;
    const top = s.pop();
    reverse(s);
    insertAtBottom(s, top);
  }
  reverse(stack);
  return stack;
}
```

**Time**: O(n^2) — each of the n elements triggers an O(n) `insertAtBottom`.
**Space**: O(n) call-stack depth × 2 from nested recursion = O(n).

**Why no iterative alternative is acceptable here**: The problem explicitly forbids auxiliary structures; iterative reversal would need a second stack or two-pointer swap (which violates the stack-only access pattern in many interview framings). Two-pointer in-place swap on the array works for this representation but breaks the spirit of the problem (it relies on random access, which a real stack doesn't provide). The recursive formulation is the canonical answer.
